<TEXT>
drug trafficking still poses a security threat 
at a topsecret nuclear weapons laboratory in california where a 
1986 undercover drug investigation was abruptly terminated under 
pressure from the energy department house investigators say 
rep john dingell dmich said a drug problem continues to 
exist a security problem continues to exist at the lawrence 
livermore national laboratory near san francisco where highly 
sensitive research on president reagans star wars missile defense 
system is conducted 
according to staff investigators for the house energy and 
commerce subcommittee chaired by dingell 
in april 1987 a livermore electronics technician with a 
highlevel security clearance was caught with several hundred 
dollars worth of illicit drugs the employee who was working on a 
classified computer system admitted trading drugs for sex with a 
female coworker 
in june 1987 a security guard responsible for protecting the 
laboratorys supersensitive plutonium facility was arrested for 
drug possession he was accused of bringing drugs and paraphernalia 
into his security bunker while on duty and being armed with an 
automatic weapon 
also last summer another employee with top security clearance 
who worked in the nuclear chemistry department resigned after he 
was accused of selling thousands of dollars worth of cocaine to 
workers in sensitive areas of the laboratory 
energy department and livermore officials are currently 
investigating allegations of drug use by a professional 
laboratory employee with access to extremely sensitive classified 
information 
dingell said these disclosures following the shutdown of the 
drug investigation codenamed operation snowstorm in september 
1986 raise serious questions about the integrity of security at 
our nations most sensitive nuclear weapons and research 
facilities 
energy undersecretary joseph f salgado said officials decided 
to terminate the investigation because it had run for eight 
months and was apparently not uncovering new productive leads 
salgado said operation snowstorm had served its purpose in 
putting livermore employees on notice that drug use would not be 
tolerated he denied dingells charge that the energy department 
had tried to conceal the aborted investigation from the house panel 
at the end of a daylong hearing wednesday dingell said he was 
ordering an audit by the general accounting office the 
investigative arm of congress to determine the extent of 
drugrelated thefts of computers and other government property at 
livermore 
if they are stealing government property why wouldnt they 
steal government secrets which are more valuable dingell asked 
energy department officials responded that they were conducting 
their own investigation of the theft problem and were 
aggressively pursuing questions of whether the laboratorys 
security clearances had been compromised by drug trafficking 
the doe was accused wednesday of halting the ninemonth drug 
investigation prematurely leaving undercover agents unable to 
pursue leads on 127 livermore employees who were suspected drug 
dealers or users 
patricia dorsadijamco a special agent of the drug enforcement 
administration testified that pressure from doe and laboratory 
officials to hasten the arrest of an alleged drug trafficking 
ringleader at livermore prevented her agency from identifying the 
drug suppliers in mexico 
rep ron wyden dore a subcommittee member suggested that 
officials who terminated the drug investigation were fearful of 
adverse publicity it seems to me that this operation snowstorm 
should be called operation snow job wyden said 
it appears that doe was less interested in cooperating with 
the dea than in heeding the concerns of one of its contractors 
dingell said he was referring to the university of california at 
los angeles which has a government contract to operate the 
livermore facility 
david a leary who managed the undercover investigation 
testified that many of the drug pushers among livermores 8500 
employees held topsecret q security clearances he said the 
illicit drugs they were selling included cocaine marijuana 
methamphetamine and barbiturates 
dingell quoted john hunt current chief of safeguards and 
security at livermore as telling staff investigators that if 
operation snowstorm had been allowed to continue we would have 
to arrest 20 percent of the lab 
security agent timothy l mitchell testified that the volume of 
illicit drug trafficking at livermore has the potential to 
endanger national security 
undercover agent robert buda told the panel he was very 
flabbergasted that the investigation was halted just three days 
before he received a q clearance to penetrate the most 
sensitive green badge areas of the laboratory 
we felt like the kid in front of the candy store said john 
c barber the university of california police chief who served as 
consultant to operation snowstorm 
we had the money in our hands and we were ready to go inside 
and do business barber said unfortunately that door closed 
before we could get it buda said 
in a jan 7 1987 memorandum obtained by the associated press 
hunt quoted adm sylvester foley assistant energy secretary for 
defense programs as offering the previous july to put pressure 
on dea to get out of our hair the dea was seeking a delay in the 
energy departments plans to halt the drug investigation in late 
summer of 1986 
