<TEXT>
dental science has developed new techniques 
and new materials for the surgical implantation of false teeth but 
there still is no definitive study on the effectiveness of the 
procedure a panel of experts says 
a panel of dental experts meeting at the national institutes of 
health released a statement wednesday in which they said more than 
300000 americans annually will be receiving surgically implanted 
false teeth by 1992 and that the number of dentists performing such 
procedures has increased by 10 times since 1983 
but the panel said scientific and statistically precise studies 
are needed to define the effectiveness of permanently implanted 
false teeth 
the panel said the cost for surgicallyinstalled false teeth is 
about 300 to 1000 per implant and that patients can receive from 
one to eight implants 
d walter cohen president of the medical college of 
pennsylvania in philadelphia and chairman of the nih conference on 
dental implants said the surgical installation of teeth can no 
longer be considered experimental 
cohen said the development of new materials and new techniques 
have led to wider acceptance of implantation by dentists and that 
the demand for permanent false teeth is increasing among americans 
he said as people tend to live longer more and more patients 
are finding that they cannot use removable false teeth and are 
choosing to have permanentlyimplanted artificial teeth 
there are several systems for implanting false teeth in living 
tissue but they all basically involve surgically cutting into the 
bone that normally supports teeth and installing a manmade peg or 
post to support the false teeth or to anchor a bridge of false 
teeth 
the nih panel said that because scientific studies have not been 
made on methods of implanting false teeth it is not possible to 
make judgments on the comparative merits of different implant 
systems 
several studies however show that dental implants are 
effective for five to 10 years the panels report said 
however the report said that little information is available to 
evaluate such factors as patient satisfaction appearance comfort 
and the effect of implants on speech and chewing 
cohen said the panel also determined that the risks of 
surgically implanting false teeth include the inadvertent 
penetration of a sinus cavity by a dentist drilling in bone to 
create a socket for the implant 
he said other problems include damage to facial nerves and 
infections that could threaten existing natural teeth 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

