<TEXT>
operating rates at american factories mines 
and utilities rose in may to 829 percent the highest level in 
more than eight years the government said today 
the federal reserve board said the 02 percentage point rise 
from the april level put operating rates at their highest levels 
since march 1980 when the rate was 837 percent 
it was the sixth increase in eight months operating rates rose 
by 03 percentage points in april after dropping 01 percent in 
february and remaining unchanged in march 
the may advance was led by gains in the production of autos and 
parts primary metals such as steel and in fabricated metal 
products it was the third consecutive steep monthly rise at motor 
vehicle and parts plants where operating rates were 839 percent 
compared with 768 percent in february 
analysts had expected the modest rise in overall operating rates 
after the federal reserve reported wednesday that production levels 
had increased 04 percent in may 
rising operating rates if unchecked are considered by analysts 
to represent a threat of inflation the concern is that prices will 
rise if manufacturers have difficulty meeting demand 
the may level of 829 percent was 3 percentage points higher 
than the 799 percent rate a year ago but analysts generally do 
not consider the overall operating rate to be inflationary until it 
reaches 85 percent 
rising capacity levels have been attributed to the surge in 
exports caused by the devaluation of the dollar but so far 
consumer demand in the united states appears to have been 
restrained enough to allow manufacturers in most industries to 
comfortably meet both domestic and foreign demand 
in a speech in new york earlier this week federal reserve 
chairman alan greenspan said despite strained capacity in steel and 
certain chemicals statistics on industrial delivery times do not 
indicate that inflationary bottlenecks are developing 
delivery times for production materials have moved up only 
moderately since late 1985 and have stabilized at least 
temporarily during the past five months he said 
the operating rate for manufacturing plants jumped to 831 
percent in may up from 829 percent a month earlier production of 
durable goods big ticket items expected to last three or more 
years rose by 06 percentage points to 816 percent while the 
rate for nondurable goods declined by 04 percentage points to 
853 percent 
the mining industry which includes oil and gas drilling 
operated at 813 percent of capacity down from 818 percent in 
april us utilities operated at an 809 percent rate in may up 
from 804 percent 
