wednesdays 85page opinion resulted from a rare en banc 
hearing of the southern district of floridas 16 federal judges 
held april 21 
its a very thorough and wellreasoned decision said benson 
weintraub a miami lawyer who spearheaded the arguments against the 
guidelines 
us district judge norman roettger whose courtroom is in fort 
lauderdale said he didnt think the change would result in widely 
different sentences 
well just sentence on the old policy thats all roettger 
said we have been sentencing as we have been for decades all 
were doing is continuing that 
the guidelines were established by the sevenmember us 
sentencing commission set up by the 1984 comprehensive crime 
control act and applied to any offense comitted after nov 1 1987 
written by us district judge stanley marcus the 124 opinion 
finds the guidelines unconstitutional primarily because of the 
composition of the sentencing commission 
because the commission includes three federal judges the 
separation of powers outlined in the us constitution is violated 
the judges said fixing punishments belongs to the legislative 
branch of government and cannot be established by judges the 
opinion said 
this collaborative rulemaking effort between the judicial and 
the executive branches of government cast too long a shadow over 
the independence and impartiality of the entire federal 
judiciary marcus wrote 
we conclude that the act is unconstitutional and until we 
receive contrary guidance from a higher authority the guidelines 
will not be applied in this district 
under the decision those who are awaiting sentencing for 
convictions or guilty pleas will be dealt with under the old 
guidelines 
richard gregorie the chief criminal prosecutor in south 
floridas us attorneys office said the justice department will 
ask that the guidelines remain in force while the decision is 
appealed 
similar hearings have been held around the country with 
conflicting opinions on the generally stricter sentencing 
guidelines included in the 1984 comprehensive crime control act 
on monday the us supreme court agreed to step into the 
dispute and a decision by the high court is expected by early next 
year said john steer general counsel to the sentencing commission 
in washington 
the guidelines allow sentencing judges to take into account the 
nature of the crime the grade of the offense the amount of harm 
caused the communitys view of the crime and the sentences 
deterrent value 
