and nine were killed by police in two shootouts near the swaziland 
border in the past week law and order minister adriaan vlok said 
the staterun south african broadcasting corp said police were 
tipped off that mozambiquebased guerrillas would try to enter 
south africa via swaziland to stage massive acts of terrorism 
in each case it said police stopped vehicles at roadblocks and 
riddled them with bullets after someone inside opened fire 
many factories shut down and the largest daily newspaper for 
blacks the sowetan did not publish workers at three diamond 
mines went on strike to demand that june 16 be designated a paid 
holiday 
the unrest came on the 12th anniversary of a police attack on 
marching schoolchildren in the black township of soweto ten 
people including two children died that june 16 the 
confrontation prompted a nationwide rampage in which hundreds were 
killed 
commemorative church services were held in many black townships 
security forces reportedly fired tear gas and bird shot because of 
stonethrowing that occurred as blacks left a church service in 
lamontville outside durban 
at langa a black township outside cape town a commuter rail 
line was bombed at midday police headquarters said two officers on 
patrol flagged down a train approaching the wrecked section of 
track averting a possible derailment 
trains coming from soweto to johannesburg reportedly were 
stoned firebombs were thrown at three buses and two delivery vans 
in other townships causing serious injuries to three blacks 
the main power line between the black township of kwamashu to 
durban was sabotaged during the night stopping rail traffic for 
several hours later a train on the route was derailed and 
commuters had to be transferred to buses 
the nations largest ports were operating normally but in the 
eastern cape province half the workers were absent at east london 
and there was a total boycott at port elizabeth docks 
mining company officials said only 24500 of 540000 black 
employees at major mines were absent the de beers mining company 
said black workers disrupted operations at three mines with a 
strike to demand that june 16 be designated a paid holiday 
it is illegal under national emergency regulations to call for 
or participate in boycotts or illegal strikes but many blacks have 
become accustomed to observing june 16 as a holiday 
in south africa there are no public holidays commemorating 
events of specific significance to the 26 million black majority 
many stores and shops in downtown johannesburg were closed and 
only a handful of buses and taxivans were operating in the city 
trains arriving from soweto and other nearby black townships were 
nearly empty 
the streets of soweto were almost deserted about 100 people 
were scattered along the main road trying to hitch rides 
most of the townships 25 million residents appeared to have 
slept late the normally teeming main bus station was vacant 
about 15 people gathered this morning in avalon cemetery at the 
grave of hector pieterson a 13yearold boy shot by police during 
the student march in soweto in 1976 
pietersons sister margot 17 and his nephew hector tabane 
6 put flowers on the grave which bears a marker saying deeply 
mourned by his parents sisters and a nation that remembers 
popi buthelezi 29 a young girl who was hurt in the 1976 
shootings came to the graveside service in a wheelchair 
the soweto students had been protesting the use of afrikaans 
the language of descendants of dutch settlers in their schools 
the shooting touched off a nationwide rampage in which by official 
count 575 blacks were killed 
the following month the government announced that blacks could 
choose the language of instruction in their schools 
the anniversary has almost always been marked by violence 
particularly confrontations between black crowds and police trying 
to halt observances 
last year 11 people died despite a call by antiapartheid 
groups for a quiet observances 
slogans were painted on the walls of the central methodist 
church in johannesburg saying castro free us south africa 
bleeds and cuba will liberate africa 
the slogans were painted in yellow green and black the colors 
of the outlawed african national congress guerrilla movement 
