<TEXT>
business inventories rose moderately as sales 
slackened in april the government said thursday in a report 
signaling slower economic growth for the second quarter 
the commerce department said inventories climbed 05 percent to 
a seasonally adjusted 7237 billion in april the gain came as 
total business sales fell 02 percent to a seasonally adjusted 
4788 billion 
the rise in goods stockpiled on shelves and backlots followed a 
03 percent climb in march and a 04 percent increase in february 
the slight drop in business sales came after a 19 percent jump in 
march the largest in more than a year and a 11 percent gain in 
february 
economists generally take rising inventories as a sign that 
buying demand is slowing and as an indication that manufacturers 
may have to cut back production 
lawrence chimerine chairman of the wefa group an economic 
forecasting service in bala cynwyd pa said april inventory 
growth was slightly disturbing and would be a real source of 
concern if it continued 
but he said he expected smaller growth in the months ahead and 
did not foresee a return to the high rate of inventory expansion 
from october to january when monthly increases ranged from 07 
percent to 12 percent 
david jones an economist with aubrey g lanston amp co a 
goverment securities dealer in new york said slower growth in the 
economy as a whole as measured by the gross national product may 
be a blessing in disguise 
the inventory numbers certainly signal the likelihood well 
grow at a slower pace maybe gnp will hit 25 percent in the second 
quarter compared with 39 percent in the first quarter jones 
said 
but that may be desireable because it could well make it 
possible to maintain more sustained growth without a sharp 
acceleration of inflationary pressure he said 
inventories in april were 79 percent higher than a year ago 
while sales were 76 percent greater 
the rise in april inventories included a 09 percent increase at 
the wholesale level a 04 percent rise in goods held by 
manufacturers and a 03 percent growth at the retail level 
the 02 percent decline in business sales was paced by 04 
percent drops in both wholesale and retail sales sales by 
manufacturers were unchanged 
in an advance report on wednesday the government said retail 
sales edged up only 01 percent in may 
the combination of falling sales and moderately rising 
inventories pushed the inventorytosales ratio up from 150 in 
march to 151 in april that means it would take 151 months to 
exhaust inventories at the april sales pace a ratio not considered 
abnormally high 
</TEXT>
