<TEXT>
the pentagon recovering from an accident in 
january has successfully resumed its testing of a chemical laser 
that one day could become a key part of any star wars antimissile 
defense system officials said thursday 
the latest test of the socalled alpha laser was conducted 
wednesday night behind closed doors at a contractors laboratory in 
san juan capistrano calif 
it marked the final checkout of all the laser components and 
support equipment and was considered a complete success said 
richard garcia a spokesman for the air force weapons laboratory at 
kirtland air force base nm 
the test replicated all the heat and pressure effects that will 
exist when a laser beam is produced in the new system but by 
design no lasing was attempted on wednesday said garcia 
the next and final stage of the testing program producing a 
highpowered laser beam through a chemical reaction will probably 
begin this fall the spokesman added 
the test conducted wednesday evening had been scheduled several 
months ago but was put off indefinitely while engineers repaired 
damage caused during a brief accidental fire on jan 7 
the fire at the trw inc laboratory resulted from an operating 
mistake by a worker little direct damage was done but the fire 
left contaminated the main vacuum chamber needed to simulate firing 
the laser in outer space and thus halted all testing 
the air force weapons laboratory completed a milestone test of 
its alpha laser on wednesday garcia said in a statement 
the laser successfully completed a hot flow test with heat 
released from the cavity this test verified that all supporting 
assemblies were operating properly and that alpha was ready to 
begin receiving the optical components necessary for full lasing 
tests 
the experiment was as close as we can get to lasing without 
actually doing it the spokesman added 
the alpha laser described by the pentagon as the most mature 
of the star wars directedenergy technologies has been under 
study for almost a decade 
the device is constructed primarily of aluminum making it 
relatively light and compact and draws its energy from the 
combustion of the gases hydrogen and fluorine it is thought to 
generate roughly 2 million watts of power 
last october the pentagon awarded a contract to martin marietta 
corp asking it to assess the possibility of conducting 
experiments in space with alpha in the meantime however trw 
which built the device began preparing for the first ground tests 
in the laboratory 
