<TEXT>
firstdegree murder trials are on hold 
until the florida supreme court can decide if the duval county 
grand jury is legal 
defense attorneys claim the jury has too many members making it 
easier for prosecutors to win an indictment 
the high court granted a stay in a murder trial scheduled to 
begin next week causing the postponement of all trials in which 
the defendants were indicted 
chief assistant state attorney john delaney said wednesday the 
ruling means none of the 17 firstdegree murder cases in duval 
county will be able to go to trial 
but delaney said the current grand jury will keep indicting 
people for firstdegree murder which carries a penalty of life in 
prison or death in the electric chair 
the high court ruling came tuesday in the case of john d 
freeman a jacksonville man already convicted and sentenced to 
death in one slaying and to go on trial monday on a second 
firstdegree murder charge 
his attorneys assistant public defenders jim miller and patrick 
mcguinness argued the case should be postponed until the grand 
jury issue is resolved 
they claim florida laws require a maximum of 18 grand jurors be 
impaneled at one time duval countys grand jury has 23 members 
they claim because it only takes 12 members to vote for an 
indictment it is easier to get 12 of 23 jurors than 12 of 18 
prosecutors however claim the legislature gives larger 
counties the right to impanel up to 23 jurors and their position 
was upheld by chief circuit judge john santora jr 
the public defenders appealed to the state supreme court 
delaney said it could be three months before the justices rule 
if the high court rules that duval county was incorrect delaney 
said a new grand jury can be impaneled and the defendants 
reindicted 
the only possibility of serious problems he said would be if 
the high court voided past convictions the county has been using 
23 grand jurors since 1970 
