<TEXT>
the pentagon has decided to stop forming 
pools of reporters to cover navy operations in the persian gulf 
and instead will try to accommodate requests from news 
organizations on an individual basis to board us warships 
the change in policy announced thursday in a brief statement 
does not change the defense departments commitment to keeping 
the american people informed about the activities of military 
personnel serving in the gulf the pentagon said 
rather the department is now going to try to accommodate the 
many requests received from news organizations asking for the 
opportunity to send representatives to ships in the persian gulf 
the statement added 
were ending the pool said dan howard assistant defense 
secretary for public affairs we will come up with a procedure 
that works for everyone this is as much a result of requests from 
various news organizations as it is at our inception 
the pentagon has operated a regional press pool in the 
persian gulf for almost a year now helping the news media to cover 
the efforts of the united states to protect reflagged kuwaiti oil 
tankers plying the waterway 
kuwait is a key ally of iraq in the iraniraq war and won 
permission from the reagan administration last year to reregister 
its ships under the us flag after they became special targets of 
iranian forces 
under the press pool procedure a small group of reporters 
representing the major wire services broadcast networks news 
magazines and daily newspapers was formed periodically and sent to 
sea with navy warships escorting tankers 
the dispatches filed by the pool reporters were then sent 
through military channels and released to all news outlets in the 
united states 
the pool system is commonly used by the press when there are 
more reporters asking to cover an event than there are spaces 
available a pool reporter is expected to share with all other 
reporters the information he gathers on the medias behalf 
according to thursdays statement the pentagon has now decided 
that absent an emergency or the outbreak of fighting there is no 
need to keep dispatching press pools to ensure coverage 
rather efforts will now be made to accommodate individual 
reporters from organizations that have not been part of the pool 
the persian gulf regional media pool will be discontinued on 
july 1 and in its place unilateral embarkations will begin with 
plans for a contingency pool as necessary the pentagon said 
the success of the regional pool was due to the cooperative 
efforts of news organizations and the department of defense to 
solve the problems faced in working in a difficult environment but 
the time has come to make this change 
the procedures for setting up regional and national press pools 
were devised in the wake of the 1983 us invasion of grenada 
during which the pentagon prohibited news coverage 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

