bill brown looked across a 30acre wheat 
field thursday at shafts of grain barely a foot tall and 
shriveling from the prolonged drought that has hit north dakota 
harder than any other state 
the best purpose for this right now is the cows he said 
digging into dirt that was bone dry three inches below the surface 
what we are trying to do now is get enough grazing to get the 
cattle through the summer 
browns farm which has received less than an inch of 
precipitation since january normally would be lush and green this 
time of year instead his pastures are parched and his grain crops 
are wilted 
brown figures the 1000 acres of wheat oats and barley that he 
planted this spring already have been wiped out we are not even 
going to start the combine this year from what i can see 
north dakota farmers are selling off cattle plowing under crops 
and filing crop insurance claims while the drought gov george 
sinner characterizes as the worst since dust bowl days grips the 
state from border to border 
the drought is expected to cost the state 40 percent of its farm 
income and seal the fate of many farmers who already were 
struggling financially 
we didnt need this said economist arlen leholm of north 
dakota state university 
the economy in north dakota was starting to rebound we had 
crop prices that were starting to rise not wildly but mildly 
livestock prices were pretty decent leholm said 
the drought could cost the states economy at least 27 
billion a loss that could throw it into another tailspin leholm 
said 
direct crop losses on wheat barley and oats will total about 
500 million because market prices are higher producers will also 
receive about 400 million less in federal deficiency payments he 
said 
we have got large sections of north dakota where they are 
estimating that 70 percent of the crop is already gone leholm 
said 
the drought is more widespread than the last one in 1980 leholm 
said the last real wipeout was in 1961 he said 
if adequate rain doesnt fall by midjuly the threshhold for 
planting later forage crops another 10 percent of the states 
farmers could be put out of business he said 
one crop insurer rain and hail insurance services already has 
