<TEXT>
the food and drug administration on thursday 
authorized expanded use of an experimental drug for parkinsons 
disease a development that could benefit 30000 americans with 
severe forms of the ailment 
the drug selegilene can be distributed under the fdas 
relatively new category called treatment ind in which promising 
experimental therapies can be prescribed for desperately ill 
patients before completion of the more extensive review required 
for fullfledged new drug approval 
selegilene is the fifth drug to win such a designation under the 
new regulations adopted last year the ind in the definition 
stands for investigational new drug 
distribution is to be administered by the drug sponsor somerset 
pharmaceuticals inc of danville nj which has an application 
pending for full approval to market the drug under the trade name 
eldepryl 
physicians treating patients with severe parkinsons who have 
had difficulty with standard treatment can contact the company for 
detailed information about the drugs distribution the fda said 
the most widely used treatment for parkinsons involves use of 
the drug levodopa however that drugs effectiveness often 
gradually decreases with longterm use and it needs to be given in 
larger amounts that can produce increasingly severe side effects 
such as nausea involuntary bodily movements flushing and 
palpitations said an fda announcement 
parkinsons disease is a serious degenerative disorder of the 
central nervous system that can affect people 40 and over it is 
believed to be caused by reduced levels of a naturally produced 
substance in the brain called dopamine 
selegilene surpresses some of the enzymes in the body that 
inactivate dopamine 
</TEXT>
