parliament has passed reforms that 
give state enterprises more say in production make them 
selffinancing and could reduce the economic bureaucracy by 30 
percent the government said thursday 
the limited package passed in a special threeday session is 
patterned after soviet reforms that prescribe selfmanagement and 
selffinancing for state enterprises and cooperatives while taking 
away some or all state subsidies 
ctk the official news agency said state companies will be 
directly subordinate to ministries and that eliminating 
middlelevel bureaus could bring a reduction of up to 30 percent in 
the economic bureaucracy 
the reforms which take effect next jan 1 were passed after a 
yearlong debate during the rest of this year companies that 
account for 30 percent of industrial production will be involved in 
an experiment that gives them greater control of production 
decisions 
czechoslovak officials gave few details on plans for economic 
reform which they approach with caution decentralization of 
management will not go as far as in the soviet union and will not 
take full effect until 1991 
premier lubomir strougal acknowledged in may that the economy 
had not improved under his government he said the number of 
committees and bureaus between enterprises and ministries will be 
reduced and the direct responsibilities of ministers increased 
the onceefficient economy is plagued by low productivity a 
poor industrial structure unbalanced supply and demand and growth 
of unsold inventory 
jaroslav matejka an architect of the reforms told a news 
conference last month only 48 percent of companies had applied for 
the new status that brings more independence he said some feared 
being put out of business 
managers will be elected by secret ballot in the plant 
according to the new law but the government retains the right to 
nominate candidates for the jobs 
