<TEXT>
the federal aviation administration flooded 
with tens of thousands of complaints from private pilots on 
thursday curtailed its proposed requirements for altitude tracking 
devices on small planes 
the faa announced a final regulation which calls for private 
pilots to have the altitude equipment when flying within 30 miles 
of 27 of the countrys busiest airports and in restricted airspace 
around 109 additional airports 
three months ago the faa said it was considering a much broader 
regulation that would have banned private pilots from airspace 
within 40 miles of 254 airports unless they had the equipment that 
tells air traffic controllers a planes altitude 
under the new rule small planes also will be prohibited from 
flying at or above 10000 feet without the altitude encoding 
equipment originally the faa had suggested requiring the equipment 
on small planes flying as low as 6000 feet 
the final regulation falls short of what the airlines had wanted 
and closer to what the private pilots of small planes had sought 
faa administrator allen mcartor said the regulation should 
reduce the danger of an aerial collision involving a small 
aircraft he called it a major positive impact on safety 
currently the altitude encoding transponders are required on 
small planes only if they fly inside controlled airspace around the 
27 busiest airports the new requirements will be phased in 
beginning in july 1989 
the move to broaden requirements for altitudereporting 
equipment stemmed from the 1986 aerial collision over cerritos 
calif in which a small plane without such equipment collided with 
a mexican airliner killing all aboard the two aircraft 
the airlines and commercial pilots have argued that small 
private planes should have the altitude encoding equipment whenever 
they fly in airspace used by commercial jetliners 
congress had called on the faa to broaden its requirement for 
the socalled modec radar signal transponders on private planes 
but when the faa suggested in february that it might require the 
equipment at 254 airports it unleashed a flurry of protests 
according to estimates by the aircraft owners and pilots 
association more than 80000 letters were sent to the faa and to 
members of congress complaining about the proposal 
the private pilot group argued that the additional signals from 
the increased number of transponders would overwhelm the air 
traffic controllers a claim disputed by the faa and that the 
additional requirements were being proposed for airspace near 
airports that are not heavily used by commercial jetliners 
pilots also complained about the estimated 600 to 2000 cost 
for the altitude encoding transponder 
commercial jets as well as most sophisticated private planes 
that fly in and out of the busiest airports already have the 
equipment 
the faa long has required any aircraft flying within socalled 
terminal control areas rings of airspace of varying size around 
the 27 busiest airports to have the altitude encoding equipment 
the rule announced thursday would require the equipment for flights 
within 30 miles of the 27 airports beginning in july 1989 
at 109 additional airports which have less restrictive 
airspace private planes must have the equipment when flying within 
that restricted area or up to 10000 feet beginning dec 30 1990 
other airports may be designated as requiring small planes to 
have the modec equipment within 10 miles but the faa said only 
two airports so far have been singled out small planes flying 
within 10 miles of billings mont and fargo nd must have the 
equipment beginning in 1991 
</TEXT>
