<TEXT>
former gov evan mecham was found innocent 
thursday of concealing a 350000 campaign loan a partial 
vindication for the first us governor impeached and removed from 
office in 59 years 
minutes after the clerk had read the jurys last not guilty 
finding on the six counts against mecham and his brother willard 
the judge declared the trial over and mechams supporters cheered 
justice can occur in arizona when you get to the people and 
outside the politicians the 64yearold former governor told 
reporters outside the court were happy were happy youre 
always apprehensive but not really surprised 
he said he would hold a news conference friday morning 
as the final verdict was read mecham smiled broadly and hugged 
his attorney michael scott then turned and embraced his wife 
florence then he crossed to the jurors and began shaking their 
hands 
scott asked judge michael ryan whether mecham could make a 
statement but the judge refused saying this is a court of law 
mr scott 
mecham had acknowledged he did not itemize the 350000 loan 
from developer and attorney barry wolfson on either his personal or 
campaign financial statements the defense said the failure was an 
innocent mistake partly due to willards inexperience as a 
bookkeeper 
however the prosecution insisted that the conservative 
republican badly needed the wolfson loan to keep his campaign 
afloat then hid it to avoid spoiling his theme of being beholden 
to no one 
the jury had deliberated 6 hours after receiving the case 
wednesday following seven days of testimony 
mecham could have been sentenced to 22 years in prison if 
convicted on all six felony counts of perjury willful concealment 
and filing false documents his 67yearold brother faced a maximum 
9 years on three counts 
attorney general bob corbin said after the verdict that he had 
offered to let mecham plead guilty to a misdemeanor before the 
trial began but mecham turned him down 
mecham was impeached by the arizona house and removed from 
office on april 4 when the state senate convicted him of misusing 
money from a state protocol fund and trying to thwart an 
investigation of a death threat he had also faced an impeachment 
trial on the loan concealment charge but the senate decided not to 
consider the matter to avoid prejudicing the criminal trial 
the former auto dealer had run for governor four times 
unsuccessfully before he won a threeway race in november 1986 
gov rose mofford the democratic secretary of state who took 
over mechams post after he was removed by the legislature said in 
a prepared statement that she hoped her predecessor and his 
entire family can resume their lives as private citizens 
the end of this trial signals a hastening of a healing process 
which has begun and that the citizens of this great state so richly 
deserve she said 
outside the courtroom prosecutor barnett lotstein said that he 
had we had an obligation to present this case and that he had 
no quarrel with the decision 
we believe we presented a responsible case that had to be 
presented we obviously felt we had a good case lotstein added 
a lot of the people in this community feel that he has suffered 
enough and perhaps that was a factor 
lotstein said he felt the key issue was whether either evan or 
willard mecham had the intent to break the law when they filled 
out the disclosure forms and that the jury obviously didnt feel 
they had such intent 
judge ryan addressing the jurors before dismissing them told 
them that this case was zealously litigated by both sides very 
well done job by both sides 
i think that your verdict has shown that there can be a fair 
verdict a fair trial for all parties in this system ryan added 
i think youre a credit to this system and i think that this 
system can do the job even under intense and high publicity 
situations 
when testimony ended friday mecham told reporters the 
prosecution had not proven its case which he said was based on 
smoke and mirrors 
neither defendant took the stand 
former top mecham aide edith richardson testified for the 
defense that the loan was common knowledge among mechams inner 
circle 
however former mecham insiders donna carlson and mac matheson 
testified that they didnt learn about the loan until october 1987 
when it was revealed by the media 
bur the prosecution said it was immaterial whether mechams 
closest aides knew about the wolfson loan the main point 
prosecutor michael cudahy said was that the loan was not listed on 
the public disclosure forms required by the state 
a state accountant leroy johnson insisted that the failure to 
list the loan could not have been simply a bookkeeping mistake by 
willard mecham 
this one transaction stands out above all other 
transactions johnson said its the largest single transaction 
by far the receipt is recorded a month after the fact the name on 
the receipt is evan mecham not barry wolfson 
the jurys makeup was an issue before selection began when 
mecham acknowledged in april that he asked a group of backers to 
remain quiet about their support of him if asked to serve on 
the jury the former governor contended he was only joking however 
mecham became engulfed in controversy just one week after taking 
office in january 1987 when he canceled a martin luther king 
holiday for some state workers on grounds it was created illegally 
he said king didnt deserve a state holiday and later caused 
another storm of criticism by defending the use of the word 
pickaninny in a book mecham also made remarks that angered 
women jews homosexuals and japaneseamericans 
the former governor also was accused of making a series of 
substandard appointments to top state positions 
before mecham the last governor impeached and removed from 
office was henry johnson of oklahoma in 1929 
