<TEXT>
the senate on thursday passed a farreaching 
welfare bill designed to help people break out of poverty through 
jobs backing it almost unanimously after acceding to white house 
demands for more stringent work requirements 
the vote on the family security act was 933 
the fiveyear 28 billion measure requires steppedup child 
support collections and creation of a comprehensive education 
training and jobs program longterm welfare recipients or those 
likely to become longterm such as teenage mothers would receive 
particular attention 
sen daniel patrick moynihan dny who wrote the bill and 
fashioned a broad coalition of senate supporters said it would 
make fundamental improvements in a system that has not changed in 
53 years 
for moynihan who was a presidential advisor and a professor 
before joining the senate the lopsided vote capped decades of 
studying and seeking welfare reform 
this is the most important legislation of its kind and the 
first legislation of its kind since the welfare system was 
established in the 1930s he exulted moynihan said that under 
the current system one child in four in this country will be on 
welfare by age 18 thats where we were headed yesterday 
senate finance committee chairman lloyd bentsen dtexas called 
the moynihan bill an opportunity to set an entirely new 
direction for the outdated and ineffective system we have today 
and senate minority leader bob dole rkan described it as 
the best hope for lifting people out of poverty and restoring 
their dignity 
voting no on the bill were sens jesse helms rnc gordon 
humphrey rnh and william proxmire dwis not voting were 
sens joseph r biden jr ddel dave durenberger rminn chic 
hecht rnev and james a mcclure ridaho 
a bipartisan group of senators negotiated with white house 
officials throughout the week following word last friday that 
reagan would veto the moynihan bill as it stood 
the main obstacle as the bill neared passage late thursday was a 
white house demand that some welfare recipients be required to 
participate for 16 hours a week in workfare or community work 
projects to work off their grants 
governors of both parties opposed the provision to phase in 
mandatory workfare participation by one adult in each twoparent 
welfare household but dole offered it as a floor amendment and the 
senate passed it by voice vote after refusing 5441 to kill it 
moynihan said the provision would affect only 6 percent to 7 
percent of the welfare caseload 
only nine states have statewide mandatory workfare programs 
some governors said it would be expensive cumbersome and 
unnecessary in their states moynihan said workfare is pointless 
for people who need retraining rather than work experience and in 
areas where the labor market is strong 
senators agreed to other white house requests as well including 
a requirement that state job and training programs include 22 
percent of eligible participants by 1994 
the agreement added about 200 million to the fiveyear cost of 
the bill bringing it up to 28 billion the house already has 
passed a more generous 7 billion welfare plan 
negotiators for each chamber will reconcile differences in the 
two bills before a plan is sent to the white house whether reagan 
supports the final measure depends largely on the extent to which 
house members are willing to go along with the senate product 
aid to families with dependent children established in 1935 as 
part of the social security system currently supports 37 million 
families which include some 7 million children 
originally conceived as a widows benefit when women 
especially mothers did not work outside the home the program now 
is dominated by divorced and unwed mothers at a time when the 
majority of new mothers are at work within a year of having a child 
the centerpiece of the house and senate bills is a new jobs 
program under which states would have to offer a wide range of 
activities including job training and basic education as well as 
actual work they would have to include as many people as they 
could afford and half the money would have to be spent on people 
needing the most help 
a 1987 study of current welfaretowork programs found that they 
did not have nearly enough money that they offered limited and 
superficial services they lacked essential support services such 
as child care put too much emphasis on job placement rates 
funneled people into lowpaying jobs that didnt get them entirely 
off welfare excluded mothers of children under 6 and tended to 
help people who really didnt need it while ignoring tough cases 
the house and senate bills attempt to correct most of these 
deficiencies each envisions a substantial federal financial 
commitment to the jobs program and describes or mandates activities 
to be offered they improve child care benefits and guarantee child 
care for people in the program mothers with children under 3 would 
be exempt from the worktraining requirement and states could 
lower that to age 1 
both bills also require states to extend welfare benefits to 
poor twoparent families the senate bill only would require the 
benefits for six months in any 12month period 26 states already 
provide yearround coverage 
a major difference in the two bills is that the house offers 
extra federal money to states that raise benefits to needy 
families which in many cases have incomes well below half the 
federal poverty line 
money to cover additional spending under the moynihan bill would 
come from making permanent a tax refund withholding program to 
recover federal debts and eliminating the business food and 
entertainment tax deduction for people with incomes over 440000 
the senate approved the meals and entertainment provision 
thursday in place of a provision phasing out the dependent care tax 
credit for higherincome families 
sen bill bradley dnj sponsor of the substitute said the 
original plan would have constituted a tax on child care and added 
im against punishing women for their professional success 
the moynihan bill attracted opposition not only from 
conservatives seeking tighter work requirements but from mothers 
who said they should not be forced to work at all a group called 
wages for housework complained that the measure was designed to 
get women off the welfare rolls not out of poverty and denigrates 
the work of all mothers 
</TEXT>
