<TEXT>
high noise levels from bagpipes can knock a 
scotsmans hearing out of kilter and even cause permanent hearing 
loss a neurologist and amateur bagpiper said thursday 
dr stephen m brittain of rutland vt and audiologist robert 
w hartenstein measured noise levels produced by the bagpipes and 
reported their findings in a letter in the june issue of the 
archives of otolaryngologyhead and neck surgery 
indoor and outdoor levels at the players left ear reached up to 
105 decibels they wrote 
noting that federal noise exposure maximums are 105 decibels for 
one hour and 115 decibels for 15 minutes they said it would be 
fairly easy for pipers to meet or exceed these limits with 
steady dedicated practice 
good quality foam ear plugs can sharply cut noise levels they 
said 
brittain who said he had been playing the pipes about three 
years became concerned when he found playing the pipes was almost 
a painful experience at first 
he said he started wearing earplugs but believes few pipers are 
aware of the risks of permanent hearing loss and few probably wear 
ear protection 
he said the ear protection he wears reduces the sound level 
about 25 decibels and does not interfere with hearing and 
evaluating his own playing 
</TEXT>
