<TEXT>
rumors the gran cafe de gijon in madrid 
might be sold to a british bank rattled coffee cups far beyond the 
centuryold literary landmark once frequented by the likes of 
ernest hemingway and truman capote 
legend has it that the actress ava gardner once punched a 
photographer there 
when the rumors spread recently of its possible sale major 
publications rushed into print with what they called the inside 
story mayor juan barranco pledged to preserve the cafe partowner 
jose lopez de brito spent a week denying it was for sale 
we are not selling it is impossible lopez told reporters 
the day reports came out that an british multinational bank not 
identified had made a 5million bid for the cafe that first 
opened its doors in 1888 
although it was before noon the gijon was already thick with 
cigar and cigarette smoke and most of its marbletop tables were 
filled 
the gijon stands just off madrids trafficclogged main 
thoroughfare the paseo de la castellana as a reminder of quieter 
days when cafes stretched across the city and coffee time was a 
ritual 
although its glory days are past and madrid is much busier in an 
economic boom the gijon still attracts dozens of tertulias 
groups of intellectuals artists or retirees who meet once or twice 
a week for relaxed conversation with a cigar over coffee and brandy 
lopez de brito said accepting the unidentified british banks 
offer would have broken a pledge made to his grandmother 
encarnation fernandez who bought the cafe from its original owners 
in 1913 
before my grandmother died she made my father and my aunt 
promise not to sell as long as my aunt is alive we wouldnt even 
consider it said lopez de brito who owns the cafe with his four 
cousins 
after that who knows he said the younger generation all 
have professional careers they want their free time the cafe 
doesnt allow that 
grandmother encarnacion and her daughter lopezs aunt maria 
presided over the gijon in the years after the 193639 spanish 
civil war when struggling actors and writers were drawn to cafes 
because of their central heating and cheap admission the price of 
a tiny cup of coffee 
by the time grateful artists showered encarnacion with drawings 
and verse on her 100th birthday in 1968 most of them were eating 
better and the gijon was a grand old survivor its fame cemented 
by the gradual demise of most competitors 
the majority of the cafes were converted into bank branches 
and the literary people took refuge here because there werent many 
places left said marias son jose garcia lopez who began 
working at the gijon in 1950 
the coffee hour was a bit sacred he said people would 
talk about their projects about bullfights they generally avoided 
politics during francos 36year rule 
pilar g nombrela who has lived above the cafe for 20 years 
said the gijon in the late 1960s was a classic cafe 
people would spend three hours over a cup of coffee and talk 
about art and literature there were tables and tables of famous 
people it was incredible 
today the tertulias are fewer at nights the cafe is 
filled with young spaniards who prefer gintonics to brandy an 
armed guard stands inside the door to keep out heroin addicts who 
have occasionally robbed patrons at knife point 
gentifrication has set in the neighborhood around the cafe and 
real estate values have shot up like the skyscrapers along the 
castellana as the spanish economy marks an annual 52 percent 
growth rate 
the cafe has changed a lot just like the country has 
changed the 63yearold garcia lopez said in those days 
there were 20 cars circulating in madrid horsedrawn carriages 
were used a lot people worked less and had more time 
madrid was a city of cafes he said one writer called it 
an archipelago of tertulias 
luis martin an octogenarian who has met at the gijon to chat 
with fellow standard electric retirees for the last two decades 
does not miss those times 
the bureacrats used to spend all day in the cafes martin 
said a few minutes before initiating a debate on the merits of 
legalizing hard drugs 
when they finally got to the office all they did was talk 
about what they had done in the cafe 
</TEXT>
