<TEXT>
us cardinals meet this month to renew debate 
over what to teach catholics about aids but if the struggles of a 
trailblazing religious education director in an affluent chicago 
parish are any indication the debate goes deeper than the 
muchpublicized condom furor aids is shaking ordinary 
parishioners deepest religious convictions and raising a central 
question is the church fundamentally about love or judgment 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
mary ann clemens nurse hospital 
chaplain mother of five and catholic educator once wrote a verse 
about trying to teach her unusual gospel of aids in this affluent 
chicago suburb 
behold 
the empty chairs and 
the quickened pace to run 
away from me who waits to 
reveal love over judgment 
knowledge over ignorance 
healing through reconciliation 
aids ministers embrace an exiled station 
behold the empty chairs 
for six years mrs clemens has been director of religious 
education at our lady of the brook a church set on 11 acres of 
lush lawns and generous parking lots 
to most in northbrook aids is as vague and distant as a foreign 
war on the evening news but in 1986 a friend of mrs clemens 
revealed his homosexuality and began drinking heavily because he 
feared getting aids later she heard from some parents that their 
children were trying alternative lifestyles including 
homosexuality 
mrs clemens came to believe that this conservative sheltered 
parish could no longer ignore the disease 
she spent 16 months writing an aids curriculum expressly for 
catholic parents from fraids to faith let us talk about 
aids told in story form blending gospel with realism about sex 
drugs and aids it was designed to help parents explain the disease 
to their children 
for fourth through sixthgraders for example there is a 
graphic discussion of bodily fluids how aids is and is not spread 
sex and marriage 
suddenly this past school year sleepy suburban northbrook found 
itself an improbable beacon of aids education 
her parish priest sunday school teachers and parents use words 
like pioneer visionary even prophet to describe mrs 
clemens who argues that aids is a cataclysmic ethical and medical 
event that raises centuriesold questions over whether the essence 
of roman catholicism is love or judgment 
despite the outward adulation however her aids gospel has been 
largely ignored she sent her curriculum to about 400 families in 
her parish but only three accepted her offer for discussions 
our homophobia is making us deny that the disease belongs to 
all of us she said 
she got brief national attention when she spoke about her 
curriculum at the national catholic education associations 
convention in new york in april she was subsequently invited to 
address other chicagoarea parishes but attracted only tiny 
audiences 
the problems she and fellow teachers have found within the 
church in some ways as intractable as the hiv virus itself are 
denial and indifference among parishioners and ambiguity and 
division in church policy 
this month she decided to leave her parish post to devote all 
her time to aids missionary work 
the story of what happened when mary ann clemens tried to get 
aids discussed in northbrook tells much about the confusion and 
moral contradictions the disease presents for catholic educators 
everywhere 
aids said mrs clemens echoing the sentiments of many 
church members is creating havoc for the catholic church 
in one sense her parish was fertile ground for trailblazing 
the chicago archdiocese led by cardinal joseph bernardin is 
comparatively liberal last december when us catholic bishops 
issued a landmark statement on aids education that included mention 
of condoms bernardin was a chief proponent 
the statement drew fire from traditionalists led by new york 
cardinal john j oconnor the nations 300 bishops have agreed to 
meet in collegeville minn june 2427 to discuss the issue again 
mrs clemens though often critical of what she considers the 
churchs lack of realism about aids never ran afoul of the 
archdiocese sister anne leonard director of catholic services of 
the chicago archdiocese and others in the hierarchy have praised 
her and her curriculum 
her pronouncements have sometimes challenged the bounds of 
acceptable dogma as when she told a gathering of nuns priests and 
lay religious teachers at the convention if a kid tells me hes 
sexually active i give condom information ill tell him how to 
put it on 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

