<TEXT>
a majority of americans questioned in a recent 
survey say the tax law that went into effect last year is less fair 
than the old statute the conference board said thursday 
the results of the poll indicate public opinion about the tax 
law has become more negative now that it has been in effect for 
more than a year 
the 5000 households questioned in the survey were asked how 
fair they felt the new law was regardless of how it affected them 
personally 
fiftythree percent said they felt the new law was less fair 
than the old law while 14 percent said they were fairer and 33 
percent said they saw little change from the old law the 
conference board said in a statement 
the results contrast with a survey taken after the new law was 
passed in 1986 at that time onethird of the respondents said the 
statute was less fair the business research organization said 
the most dissatisfaction with the new law came from upperincome 
households those with incomes above 50000 a year in that group 
62 percent said the new statute was less fair 15 percent said it 
was fairer and 23 percent said they saw no change 
fortysix percent of the overall respondents in the latest 
survey said their taxes have gone up since the new law was 
implemented while 36 percent said their taxes were the same and 18 
percent said they were lower 
among upperincome respondents 63 percent reported their taxes 
were higher 21 percent said they were the same and 16 percent said 
they were lower 
the survey which has a margin of error of plus or minus 1 
percent was conducted for the conference board by national family 
opinion inc based in toledo ohio 
