<DOCNO> AP880616-0263 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
japans muscular economy shrugging off the burden 
of a strong currency grew faster in the first three months of 1988 
than at any time since 1977 according to figures released thursday 
boosted by personal spending and housing investment the economy 
grew 27 percent in the januarymarch period after adjustment for 
inflation the economic planning agency said 
that came to an unusually robust annual growth rate of 113 
percent the fastest since the januarymarch period of 1977 when 
the annual growth rate was 117 percent records show 
although growth rates tend to fluctuate erratically from quarter 
to quarter economists said the increase was nevertheless an 
impressive sign of strength 
the first three months of 1988 represent the final quarter of 
japans 1987 fiscal year growth for the entire fiscal year came to 
49 percent after adjustment for inflation more than in the united 
states and western europe the agency said 
a year ago economic planners were worried that the soaring 
value of the japanese yen would drive the economy into a recession 
by making japanese exports too expensive for foreign purchasers 
instead the value of the yen stabilized and japanese companies 
found ways to cut costs and keep their prices competitive in world 
markets 
it is easy for many japanese exporters to overcome this yen 
increase now theyre feeling very comfortable exporting many 
goods to not only the united states but many asian countries and 
european countries said yoshihisa kitai a new yorkbased 
economist for the long term credit bank of japan 
at the same time the economy has become less dependent on 
exports because of a governmentfueled expansion of the domestic 
economy the government has provided easy credit and undertaken a 
multitrillionyen housing and public works program 
the 1987 real growth rate of 49 percent topped the governments 
revised target of 37 percent for real growth that is growth 
after adjusting for the effects of inflation the government 
predicted real growth of 38 percent in fiscal 1988 
officials said personal spending which normally accounts for 
about 55 percent of japans gross national product rose 40 
percent in fiscal 1987 from a year earlier 
housing investment rose by 239 percent and industrial equipment 
investment rose by 101 percent both compared with fiscal 1986 
the official said 
housing investment softened at the end of the fiscal year 
housing starts in january february and march were up 2 percent 
from a year earlier after a string of doubledigit increases 
however consumer spending in the quarter was strong an 
additional shopping day in february helped boost consumer spending 
said shingo unami an economist for yasuda trust and banking co 
japans growth outpaced the growth in the 1987 calendar year of 
29 percent in the united states 48 percent in britain 17 
percent in west germany 22 percent in france and 31 percent in 
italy but trailed the growth of 120 percent in south korea 
officials said 
</TEXT>
