<TEXT>
a group of leading european 
industrialists on wednesday criticized rules for regulating mergers 
that has been proposed by the european economic community 
commission 
in a statement the european roundtable said parts of the 
proposals were unclear or unworkable echoing similar criticisms 
leveled last month by unice a federation of employer organizations 
the eec commission says merger rules are necessary as the 
12nation bloc moves to create a unified market by 1992 and has 
proposed that it be given the power to block mergers judged to be 
anticompetitive 
the roundtable which consists of about three dozen big 
companies said that it was concerned that the present draft of 
the merger regulation doesnt sufficiently support corporate 
restructuring 
it said the commission should only be able to block a merger if 
it could show that competition would be eliminated in the 
relevant market 
it also said any control by the commission should allow 
companies to make rapid decisions so that possible mergers would 
not fail simply due to administrative procedures 
