<TEXT>
the us justice department is investigating 
northrop corps payment of more than 7 million to korean 
businesses in connection with its attempts to sell its f20 jet 
fighter to the korean military an official familiar with the case 
said thursday 
the criminal probe which seeks to determine if the payments in 
1984 through 1986 violated the foreign corrupt practices act is in 
its preliminary stages said the official who refused to be 
identified the act bars us companies from making direct or 
indirect payments to foreign government officials 
the investigation first reported in thursdays wall street 
journal apparently parallels a congressional committee inquiry 
into northrops payments to korean companies that were made in 
connection with negotiations for sale of the fighter planes 
northrop isnt aware of the justice department probe spokesman 
tony cantafio said thursday at the companys los angeles 
headquarters 
the company previously has portrayed itself as a victim of fraud 
by the korean companies it dealt with and has sued in korean 
courts for return of its money 
korea decided against buying the f20 which northrop never put 
into production because of a lack of orders worldwide 
northrop said it invested 65 million in a korean hotel venture 
as part of a legal offset agreement to demonstrate that in 
return for the jet contract the company was willing to help boost 
the korean economy the probe by a subcommittee of the house energy 
and commerce committee focuses on that payment along with 
northrops payment of 15 million to terminate a lobbying 
agreement with a company controlled by the late park chongkyu a 
businessman well connected with the korean government 
the justice department will investigate a secret agreement for 
northrop to pay as much as 55 million to parks company if the 
lobbyist persuaded the korean government to buy 200 of the fighter 
planes sources told the journal 
</TEXT>
