<TEXT>
itoyokado co a major japanese supermarket chain 
has suspended sales of south african products because of the 
countrys apartheid policy a company official said thursday 
the decision not to deal in south african products was made in 
view of the growing criticism in and outside the company against 
the nations discriminatory policy of racial segregation said 
yasuo takaha spokesman for the company 
as a result of the decision sales of canned yellow peaches 
canned fruit cocktail and a mixed fruit juice all imported through 
a japanese trading company were suspended at the companys 133 
stores across japan in april 
takaha said the decision was made during a company meeting in 
march but the supermarket chain deliberately did not make a formal 
announcement he said the products have been replaced with similar 
items from the united states 
takaha also declined to provide sales figures for the two south 
african products itoyokado has sold the canned peaches since 1983 
and the fruit cocktail since 1985 
the move by the retailer comes at a time when japan is facing 
rising international criticism over its trade with south africa 
last year japan became south africas largest trading partner 
surpassing west germany and the united states 
in dollar terms japans twoway trade with south africa rose 19 
percent to 427 billion last year according to preliminary 
japanese figures 
japan currently prohibits all direct investment by local 
companies in south africa bans imports of south african iron and 
steel and limits cultural sports and tourism exchanges it also 
bans sales of computers that might be used to enforce the apartheid 
system 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

